column10:
If you enjoy Slay The Spire, this game is an easy pick up. For me, Monster Train differs itself from STS in the turn planning process. This is due to two main reasons: 
-Your opponents typically take their turn before you;
-The multiple floors on the train add a new planning dimension.

An amazing and polished deck building rogue-like game.

If you like "Slay the Spire" game, you should definitely try this one too. And vise-versa, though I have feeling this game is in many ways superior. I will compare them for you:

+ shorter game sessions: just 9 battles;
+ each battle can be easily replayed (unless crystal is destroyed) by exiting to main menu and loading the game;
+ battles are more "strategic": 3 floors and few waves before fighting mini-/maxy-/end-boss;
+ no "bad" events, anything what happens is either good or can be skipped;
+ "smart" shuffle cards: there is guaranteed unit accompany the hero, similar cards aren't bundled, etc.;
+ no need to build "perfect rotation" decks, it's relatively easy to remove cards and upgrade, though both are limited;
+ there are just 2 path to select one after each fight;
+ there are many things to master after beating the game (which for me is to complete all the achievements).

Random can still hurt, especially on a higher difficulties, when starting deck is bloated with mostly poor cards. Removing cards is easy. Upgrading units or spells cards is always a hard choice as well as maintaining a crystal health.

Be careful when playing this game at late times, you may accidentally spend a whole night ;)
